>(7.9&#x02013;12.2)</td><td rowspan="1" colspan="1">&#x0003c;0.0001</td></tr></tbody></table><table-wrap-foot><fn><p>Shading shows statistically significant results.</p></fn></table-wrap-foot></table-wrap><p>When viewed over the whole of these 12&#x02005;h periods, in the night-time, there were no significant differences in median core or peripheral temperatures between swaddled infants and those in sleeping-bags in either Gers or apartments (<xref ref-type="table" rid="ARCHDISCHILD2014307908TB3">tables 3</xref> and <xref ref-type="table" rid="ARCHDISCHILD2014307908TB4">4</xref>). Overall in 24&#x02005;h (<xref ref-type="table" rid="ARCHDISCHILD2014307908TB2">table 2</xref>), the core body temperature was also slightly but significantly higher in the swaddled group at 1&#x02005;m. Despite these differences, however, the peripheral temperatures of the non-swaddled infants (a marker of peripheral vasoconstriction in response to cold stress) were not lower than those of the swaddled infants, suggesting that both groups of infants were in thermoneutral conditions.</p><table-wrap id="ARCHDISCHILD2014307908TB4" orientation="portrait" position="float"><label>Table&#x000a0;4</label><caption><p>Daytime and night-time median temperatures of 3-month-old infants in Gers and apartments</p></caption><table frame="hsides" rules="groups"><colgroup span="1"><col align="left" span="1"/><col align="char" char="." span="1"/><col align="char" char="." span="1"/><col align="char" char="." span="1"/><col align="char" char="." span="1"/><col align="char" char="." span="1"/><col align="char" char="." span="1"/><col align="char" char="." span="1"/><col align="char" char="." span="1"/><col align="char" char="." span="1"/><col align="char" char="." span="1"/></colgroup><thead valign="bottom"><tr><th align="left" colspan="11" rowspan="1">Three-month-old infants in Gers</th></tr><tr><th align="left" colspan="6" rowspan="1">Daytime</th><th align="left" colspan="5" rowspan="1">Night-time</th></tr>